### Project Overview

### Module structures/usage
- The semantic approach is preferred because:
  - Less verbose - shorter, cleaner names
  - Context-aware - the parent module provides context
  - Follows conventions - many Python libraries use this pattern
  - Easier to read - from search import generic reads naturally
- The pattern: parent_module.semantic_name where the semantic name is concise and the parent provides context.
- don't use __init__ files if you don't have to; they bloat the project
- generally, we prefer simpler directory/file/package/module structures
- always use absolute imports for modules

### Misc
- always use loguru instead of print statements for logging
- always use the Pathlib Path object for file paths/file manipulation
- try and hoist common variables into configuration if possible
- always use sqlmodel and pydantic models for database operations